snapshot.eval/tests/unit/assertion-classification:
{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the classification on a_012 — the death certificate birth fact for Patrick Flynn."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should explain why source_classification stays 'original' even though information_quality is secondary — the three layers are independent (the 1908 death certificate is itself an original source; the informant being distant from the event affects information quality, not source classification)",
    "Should explain why the son-in-law is a secondary informant for Patrick's birth (James Brown was not present at his father-in-law's birth six decades earlier) — citing the relationship and the temporal gap",
    "Should populate `informant_bias_notes` flagging that Brown may have confused Patrick's place of residence with his place of birth (the death cert says Pennsylvania, but the census records say Ireland — the conflict resolution in c_001 favored Ireland)"
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_002",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "I have a new census record. Extract the assertions and classify them properly."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should route to record-extraction rather than treating the request as a classification-refinement task"
  ],
  "negative": {
    "correct_skill": [
      "record-extraction"
    ],
    "explanation": "The user wants assertions extracted from a new record. record-extraction's job is to produce new assertion entries from records; it does the initial classification at extraction time. assertion-classification only operates on existing assertions to refine their classification layers — it doesn't create new assertions from raw record data."
  },
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_003",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "negative"
  }
}

{
  "input": {
    "scenario": "mid-research-flynn",
    "user_message": "Review the evidence classification for assertion a_001."
  },
  "judge_context": [
    "Should distinguish the census enumerator (recorder) from the informant — name facts in 1850 censuses don't have an identified informant; the enumerator may have read a sign, asked a neighbor, or asked a household member, and the census doesn't say which",
    "Should keep `informant_proximity: \"unknown\"` for name facts in the 1850 census (this is the correct conservative classification), OR if the skill argues for `household_member`, the rationale must explain why a name fact specifically requires active reporting (which it doesn't — names can be inferred from a doorplate or neighbor)",
    "Should keep `evidence_type: \"direct\"` for a_001 — the assertion was extracted for q_002 ('Where was Patrick Flynn in the 1850 census?'), and finding Patrick Flynn in the census record IS the direct answer to that question. The name assertion identifies the subject within the record, which directly answers q_002. Changing evidence_type to 'indirect' would be incorrect here."
  ],
  "test": {
    "id": "ut_assertion_classification_001",
    "skill": "assertion-classification",
    "type": "positive"
  }
}

